rthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Tulloch, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lennox","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: habitational name from the districtnear Dumbarton, recorded in 1174 in the form <i>Leuenaichs</i> and inthe following year as <i>Levenax</i>. Apparently it is named fromGaelic <i>leamhan</i> ‘elm’ + the locative suffix <i>-ach</i> +English <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Lenox","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   Lennox  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Lennox was born in 1295, in Tulloch, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. She had at least 3 sons with Donnachadh Rearhair de Atholia 5th Laird Of Athol. She died in Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1295–":"1295–Surnud","1290–1355":"1290–1355","1328–1392":"1328–1392","1330–1392":"1330–1392","1295–Female":"1295–Surnud","about 1328":"umbes 1328","1355":"1355","1330":"1330","1295":"1295","about 1330":"umbes 1330","1392":"1392","1328":"1328","1290":"1290","Struan, Perthshire, Scotland":"Struan, Perthshire, Scotland","Rannoch, Perthshire, Scotland":"Rannoch, Perthshire, Scotland","Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Tulloch, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Tulloch, Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1295–":"1295–Kuollut","1290–1355":"1290–1355","1328–1392":"1328–1392","1330–1392":"1330–1392","1295–Female":"1295–Kuollut","about 1328":"noin 1328","1355":"1355","1330":"1330","1295":"1295","about 1330":"noin 1330","1392":"1392","1328":"1328","1290":"1290","Struan, Perthshire, 